-- Market Chatter-Corporate finance press digest
-- 
-- Wed Oct 08, 2014 12:14AM EDT
-- None



Oct 8 (Reuters) - The following corporate finance-related stories were reported by media:

* Telecom Italia's <TLIT.MI> Brazilian unit is considering investing an extra 750 million euros ($948.53 million) over three years to improve its local mobile phone network, according to a person with knowledge of the plan, as the Italian company tries to regain momentum in a key market. [ID:nL6N0S23M9]  * Deutsche Bank <DBKGn.DE> is preparing to sell a $2 billion portfolio of U.S. commercial real estate loans as the North American property markets heat up, a source familiar with the matter said on Tuesday. [ID:nL6N0S24MU]  * Dutch private equity group Waterland is in exclusive talks to buy Median Kliniken, Germany's largest private sector chain of health rehabilitation clinics, two people familiar with the matter told Reuters. [ID:nL6N0S2313]  * The trustee of Hubbell Inc's <HUBb.N> <HUBa.N> controlling family trusts is evaluating alternatives for their holdings, which may lead to a shakeup at the $7.2 billion U.S. electrical equipment maker, according to people familiar with the matter. [ID:nL2N0S12GB]  * Irish cement maker CRH Plc <CRH.I> has teamed up with Mexican rival Cemex <CMXCPO.MX> to explore a bid for all the assets industry giants Lafarge <LAFP.PA> and Holcim <HOLN.VX> must sell to get the go-ahead for their planned merger from competition watchdogs, according to several people familiar with the matter. [ID:nL6N0RX4RW]  * Telecom operator Swisscom AG <SCMN.VX> is considering a possible sale of its Italian broadband firm Fastweb, which is worth up to 5 billion euros and has been a target for Vodafone <VOD.L>, sources familiar with the situation said. [ID:nL6N0S24E2]  * Actavis Plc <ACT.N> plans to approach Allergan Inc <AGN.N> again about a potential merger, as the Botox maker warms up to the possibility of a sale, people familiar with the matter said on Tuesday. [ID:nL2N0S22B9]  * Buyout firm Vista Equity Partners is in talks to acquire TransFirst Inc, a payment processing company that has filed for an initial public offering, for as much as $1.5 billion including debt, according to people familiar with the matter. [ID:nL6N0S23OU]  * Germany's Bertelsmann <BTGGg.F> plans to increase its stake in book publisher Penguin Random House as early as next year, Bloomberg News reported, citing people familiar with the matter. [ID:nL6N0S240C]  * Global miner Anglo American Plc <AAL.L> is planning to initiate the sale of its three smallest copper mines in Chile and a smelter worth $1 billion by end of the year, Bloomberg reported, citing sources familiar with the matter. [ID:nL2N0S22KF]  * Security software maker Symantec Corp <SYMC.O> is in advanced talks to split its business into two entities - one that sells security programs and another that does data storage, Bloomberg reported, citing people with knowledge of the matter. [ID:nL3N0S30RI]  * Royal Dutch Shell Plc's <RDSa.L> 327,000-barrel-per-day (bpd), joint-venture Deer Park, Texas, refinery has pushed back the planned restart of its 70,000 bpd gasoline-producing fluidic catalytic cracking unit to the end of the week, sources familiar with refinery operations said on Tuesday. [ID:nL2N0S221R]  * U.S. private equity fund TA Associates is in advanced talks with the promoters of Famy Care Ltd and private equity investor AIF Capital to purchase a 35 percent stake in the unlisted Mumbai-based generic oral contraceptive pills and hormone drug maker for $200 million, the Economic Times reported, citing people familiar with the deal. (http://bit.ly/1oP6V9o)  * India's largest power producer NTPC Ltd <NTPC.NS> is evaluating a proposal to buy stranded power assets worth $5 billion, in contrast with its earlier strategy of taking the greenfield route to add capacity, the Times of India reported, citing sources. (http://bit.ly/1CTvwSQ)   For the deals of the day click on [DEALS/]